<TEXT>
A car burst into flames early today about 40 yards 
from Prime Minister Margaret Thatchers official London residence 
and office killing the driver and police said no explosives were 
found 
Police bomb squad officers raced to 10 Downing St shortly after 
midnight fearing a possible terrorist attack 
However Scotland Yard later said in a statement There was no 
trace of an explosive device It added At no time did the car 
make any attempt to enter Downing Street and therefore the prime 
minister was not in any danger 
Independent Radio News said the victim had been out of work for 
over a year and had killed himself to protest unemployment The 
unemployment rate in December was 97 percent 
The British domestic news agency Press Association said gasoline 
cans were believed to have been found inside the car and that one 
theory was that the driver deliberately started the fire in order 
to commit suicide 
Scotland Yard refused to comment on the reports or to identify 
the badly burned driver pending an autopsy 
The London Evening Standard identified the driver as Derek 
Bainbridge from Worksop in central England and said he gave up his 
job as a street sweeper 14 months ago 
Mrs Thatchers office in a statement confirmed that the prime 
minister had been at 10 Downing Street at the time of the incident 
The Scotland Yard spokesman speaking anonymously said police 
did not yet know what caused the green Vauxhall Viva auto to burst 
into flames at the entrance to Downing Street from Whitehall the 
main thoroughfare in the area 
A car pulled up in Whitehall at the entrance to Downing Street 
and burst into flames The fire was put out by London Fire Brigade 
and the body of a man was found inside the car the Scotland Yard 
statement said 
The incident was witnessed by a police officer on duty at the 
metal security barriers that separate Downing Street from Whitehall 
The car had been traveling down Whitehall from the direction of 
Parliament Scotland Yard said Whitehall was sealed off for about 
three hours as police investigated the burnedout auto before 
removing it 
Police estimated that the car was about 40 yards from Mrs 
Thatchers residence Downing Street is a very short deadend 
street with No 10 located toward the far end from Whitehall 
